00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:49.700
So what is Shiny Live?

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:51.700
Normally when we run Shiny,

00:07:51.700 --> 00:07:56.339
you have your traditional server, centralized server.

00:07:56.339 --> 00:07:59.660
And in this case, we would have three users come in

00:07:59.660 --> 00:08:03.220
and they would want to look at the Shiny application.

00:08:03.220 --> 00:08:05.420
In this case, R is actually running

00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:06.899
in the centralized server.

00:08:06.899 --> 00:08:09.899
There's gonna be like one instance of R

00:08:09.899 --> 00:08:12.500
and the users just have a website.

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:13.899
There's nothing on their machines.

00:08:13.899 --> 00:08:18.820
It's just like going to a different website, like normal.

00:08:21.459 --> 00:08:25.739
It works well because everything is hidden in the server.

00:08:25.739 --> 00:08:28.260
The users only get the minimal amount of information.

00:08:28.299 --> 00:08:30.619
And then this allows your server to be,

00:08:30.619 --> 00:08:32.460
you can have it be really beefy

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:37.099
and it can do all the heavy lifting for your users.

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:41.940
Where in Shiny Live,

00:08:41.940 --> 00:08:45.900
what we do is we actually take that centralized server

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:49.219
and instead we send it to each of the user's browsers.

00:08:50.340 --> 00:08:53.900
And that in itself is just kind of crazy.

00:08:53.900 --> 00:08:55.580
We'll go into that more later,

00:08:55.580 --> 00:08:59.900
but what we do is it's now distributed to the user.

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:02.380
And so the user has both the server,

00:09:02.380 --> 00:09:05.020
like the backend and the front end on their machine.

00:09:06.020 --> 00:09:08.859
Disadvantages, they're not communicating with each other.

00:09:08.859 --> 00:09:10.900
There's no centralized server,

00:09:10.900 --> 00:09:14.340
but advantages, it scales really well.

00:09:14.340 --> 00:09:16.580
I mean, you can have as many users as you want

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:18.739
because they just download the whole thing.

00:09:20.619 --> 00:09:22.539
Now there's no centralized server

00:09:22.539 --> 00:09:23.940
and this can be done through something

00:09:23.940 --> 00:09:26.900
like a static hosting website, like GitHub Pages.

00:09:30.979 --> 00:09:34.820
So let's look at that kick.

00:09:44.380 --> 00:09:48.099
So I clicked on the link and I promise you

00:09:48.099 --> 00:09:50.780
my personal website, I do not have a server.

00:09:50.820 --> 00:09:52.460
I am an open source.

00:09:52.460 --> 00:09:54.619
I don't like to pay for things.

00:09:54.619 --> 00:09:58.340
So when I go to it and I refresh it,

00:09:58.340 --> 00:10:01.580
things are cached and the app is fully loaded.

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:05.380
And like R is already in the browser, R already is here.

00:10:05.380 --> 00:10:08.539
And the UI obviously is here as well,

00:10:08.539 --> 00:10:11.179
but everything is there in that browser tab

00:10:11.179 --> 00:10:13.179
and it's all self-contained.

00:10:13.179 --> 00:10:17.940
And it kind of feels like a anticlimactic reveal

00:10:17.940 --> 00:10:21.580
because you're like, it's just a Shiny app.

00:10:21.580 --> 00:10:22.820
What's the big deal?

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:25.500
But it's, I promise it's all there

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:29.539
and it's delivered statically and nothing is going on.

00:10:29.539 --> 00:10:31.539
And that's just the power of Shiny Live.

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:33.859
All right.

00:10:35.739 --> 00:10:38.460
So how is Shiny Live even possible?

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:41.340
And I think this is the most sincere slide.

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:44.460
It's just legit magic.

00:10:45.380 --> 00:10:46.219
There's,

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:51.340
if you were to ask me at any time point

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:53.580
before maybe two years ago and say,

00:10:53.580 --> 00:10:55.500
can R be put on the internet?

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:58.700
I would have laughed and bet you a dollar immediately.

00:10:58.700 --> 00:11:02.020
And today I am very happy to be wrong

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:03.380
and lose that dollar bet.

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:08.380
Even as Joe said, as Eric said, Joe said in his keynote,

00:11:08.380 --> 00:11:12.380
like I'm skeptical, but like, if it can happen,

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:14.020
let's give it a go.

00:11:15.219 --> 00:11:19.140
And it all hinges on having R in the browser.

00:11:20.900 --> 00:11:22.739
So who did this?

00:11:22.739 --> 00:11:23.580
George Stagg.

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:27.099
He's the gentleman we all have to thank

00:11:28.099 --> 00:11:31.619
because as the web started shifting towards

00:11:31.619 --> 00:11:33.619
let's put everything into the browser,

00:11:33.619 --> 00:11:37.900
he was ready to take on that challenge.

00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:42.580
And, you know, Shiny Live would not exist without him.

00:11:43.219 --> 00:11:47.500
I highly recommend you to look at his blog

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:51.299
and his website, gws.phd.

00:11:51.299 --> 00:11:55.900
And he's also the maintainer of WebR

00:11:55.900 --> 00:11:58.500
where the true magic of Shiny Live comes in.

00:12:00.539 --> 00:12:04.179
WebR, excuse me, WebR is where a lot

00:12:04.179 --> 00:12:05.380
of the heavy lifting is done.

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:08.419
And then Shiny Live is just kind of like the icing on top.

00:12:08.419 --> 00:12:11.539
So while I'm doing this workshop and presenting

00:12:11.539 --> 00:12:15.380
as I'm the developer, really the hats off

00:12:15.380 --> 00:12:16.739
need to go to George Stagg.

00:12:16.739 --> 00:12:19.700
I get to just present the cherry on top of the cake.

00:12:19.700 --> 00:12:21.539
Like he's done the heavy lifting

00:12:21.539 --> 00:12:24.500
and I want to be, we're all thankful for him.

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:30.659
Also there's rwasm actions.

00:12:30.659 --> 00:12:33.419
So if you're doing anything for your company

00:12:33.419 --> 00:12:38.419
that is behind private GitHub or other things of the sort,

00:12:39.419 --> 00:12:41.460
but you do have access to GitHub,

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:43.580
rwasm actions will be your friend

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:46.500
and you can help set up your own private grand instances,

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:51.059
things like that to help enable Shiny Live to work better.

00:12:54.979 --> 00:12:58.859
So if George Stagg is a magician, what is it?

00:12:58.859 --> 00:13:00.020
You know, it's always kind of fun

00:13:00.020 --> 00:13:01.700
to see how the magic works.

00:13:01.700 --> 00:13:04.500
So what is Shiny Live built upon?

00:13:06.820 --> 00:13:08.099
And there's a little bit of rabbit hole,

00:13:08.780 --> 00:13:10.419
a little bit of a nerdy rabbit hole,

00:13:10.419 --> 00:13:12.820
but I do feel like we should go down it

00:13:12.820 --> 00:13:14.820
because it kind of feels like,

00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:16.820
oh, I should just have R,

00:13:16.820 --> 00:13:19.979
I install R through the installer on the server

00:13:19.979 --> 00:13:20.820
and then we're done.

00:13:20.820 --> 00:13:23.780
Like that's kind of how it normally works,

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:25.219
but it's all in your browser

00:13:25.219 --> 00:13:27.619
and the browser is just looking for a website.

00:13:27.619 --> 00:13:31.619
So it's kind of neat to see how that sauce is made.

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:37.539
So Shiny Live, Shiny Live runs Shiny entirely in the browser

00:13:37.539 --> 00:13:39.619
without any need for a hosted server

00:13:39.619 --> 00:13:43.299
using WebAssembly via the WebR project.

00:13:43.299 --> 00:13:44.140
Link to that.

00:13:47.460 --> 00:13:50.460
And then Shiny Live uses WebR according to the description.

00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:52.059
So what is WebR?

00:13:52.059 --> 00:13:54.820
WebR is a version of statistical language R

00:13:54.820 --> 00:13:56.140
compiled for the browser

00:13:56.140 --> 00:13:59.500
and Node.js using WebAssembly via Emscripten.

00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:02.900
There is some fun rumblings right now

00:14:02.900 --> 00:14:05.059
about talking about Node.js.

00:14:06.059 --> 00:14:08.900
So right now we're doing things with the browser,

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:10.059
but it would be kind of neat

00:14:10.059 --> 00:14:13.140
if we could have Node.js running in our instance

00:14:14.219 --> 00:14:17.859
just for portability and reproducibility purposes.

00:14:20.659 --> 00:14:22.580
WebR talked about Emscripten.

00:14:22.580 --> 00:14:23.780
So what is Emscripten?

00:14:24.859 --> 00:14:26.140
These are all terms,

00:14:26.140 --> 00:14:29.380
things that I had to learn over the past couple of years.

00:14:29.380 --> 00:14:32.820
Emscripten is complete compiler tool chain

00:14:33.059 --> 00:14:35.460
to WebAssembly using LLVM

00:14:35.460 --> 00:14:39.500
with a special focus on speed, size, and the web platform.

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:42.020
This is where I start to get a little fuzzy.

00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:45.979
I'm more of a front-end R.

00:14:45.979 --> 00:14:47.179
This isn't my area,

00:14:47.179 --> 00:14:50.059
but George gets very, very excited

00:14:50.059 --> 00:14:52.859
when he gets to hang out in this land a little bit more.

00:14:55.780 --> 00:14:58.299
And then finally, what is WebAssembly?

00:14:59.260 --> 00:15:02.700
WebAssembly, abbreviated WASM,

00:15:02.700 --> 00:15:05.340
is a binary instruction format

00:15:05.340 --> 00:15:07.619
for a stack-based virtual machine.

00:15:09.140 --> 00:15:11.140
WASM is designed as a portable compilation target

00:15:11.140 --> 00:15:12.380
for programming languages,

00:15:12.380 --> 00:15:13.659
enabling deployment on the web

00:15:13.659 --> 00:15:15.619
for client and server applications,

00:15:15.619 --> 00:15:18.580
and it's supported by all major browsers.

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:22.059
This is a really, really interesting concept

00:15:22.059 --> 00:15:24.179
because it feels like...

00:15:24.179 --> 00:15:25.739
Like the comparison I like to think of

00:15:25.739 --> 00:15:28.340
is it's like Docker for your web browser.

00:15:29.419 --> 00:15:32.940
You can, instead of having Docker on your desktop

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:34.940
or your container and Kubernetes or whatever,

00:15:34.940 --> 00:15:39.940
instead you could have your information bundled up

00:15:40.380 --> 00:15:42.780
and then you just open it in your web browser

00:15:42.780 --> 00:15:44.619
versus saying Docker run.

00:15:45.619 --> 00:15:47.700
And WebAssembly just allows for that now

00:15:47.700 --> 00:15:50.859
and it's supported within all those browsers.

00:15:56.739 --> 00:15:59.020
I talked about how it's kind of bundled

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:02.619
and this really helps drive reproducibility

00:16:02.619 --> 00:16:06.020
and that's always a big plus in the R community.

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:08.539
How R Markdown and now Cordo

00:16:09.619 --> 00:16:11.820
are doing these reproducible documents.

00:16:11.820 --> 00:16:13.859
You can do all your research in there

00:16:13.859 --> 00:16:17.219
and then you can recompile it and it'll all show up again.

00:16:18.059 --> 00:16:20.940
With WASM, you really want to have something to say,

00:16:20.940 --> 00:16:23.020
I want to save this app in a bundle

00:16:23.020 --> 00:16:24.179
and I want to have it saved

00:16:24.179 --> 00:16:25.700
and I want it to work forever.

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:27.739
How can I do this?

00:16:27.739 --> 00:16:32.739
And it's really important that you can have something

00:16:33.780 --> 00:16:37.380
that is platform neutral and you can also have...

00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:39.619
It's just a binary that you can just kind of ship around

00:16:39.619 --> 00:16:42.979
almost like a zip folder and it'll be really big

00:16:42.979 --> 00:16:45.059
because you're gonna have WASM,

00:16:45.059 --> 00:16:47.020
you're gonna have the compiled R system,

00:16:47.020 --> 00:16:49.260
you're gonna have extra libraries.

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:52.179
So if your app is a little bit on the larger size

00:16:52.179 --> 00:16:56.179
and including your data, you might have a 500 meg bundle,

00:16:56.179 --> 00:16:59.299
but that's okay because anyone can open that up

00:16:59.299 --> 00:17:02.500
and if they had local hosting applied,

00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:04.020
they could kind of open it up

00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:08.699
with their Wi-Fi turned off and Shiny will work

00:17:08.699 --> 00:17:10.739
and Shiny Live will work and run.

00:17:11.619 --> 00:17:13.859
And it's very, very exciting with that

00:17:13.859 --> 00:17:18.859
because the place where it's being hosted

00:17:19.020 --> 00:17:21.140
does not need to have their own version of R

00:17:21.140 --> 00:17:22.819
and they can have their own version of R installed,

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:25.780
can have conflicting versions of R in different bundles

00:17:25.780 --> 00:17:28.780
because it doesn't matter, they're just in different bundles.

00:17:31.739 --> 00:17:35.180
I do want to point out that the WASM

00:17:35.180 --> 00:17:38.859
is not completely 100% reproducible.

00:17:39.739 --> 00:17:42.540
There is some non-determinism places

00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:46.579
that they are aware of and are saying is allowed

00:17:46.579 --> 00:17:49.900
and the website that they have,

00:17:49.900 --> 00:17:51.819
I'll still go into that a little bit more.

00:17:54.819 --> 00:17:55.660
Libby.

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:00.140
Yeah.

00:18:01.459 --> 00:18:02.300
Let's see.

00:18:04.420 --> 00:18:05.739
Here we go.

00:18:05.739 --> 00:18:08.420
So I do want to point out some interesting ones

00:18:08.420 --> 00:18:12.780
that I had George ask me about

00:18:12.780 --> 00:18:16.380
and it's like, why not Docker?

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:19.219
Why not do any of like, you know,

00:18:19.219 --> 00:18:20.859
Docker has been solved, has big team,

00:18:20.859 --> 00:18:23.219
like why not use them?

00:18:23.219 --> 00:18:25.660
And one of the examples that he was able to show me

00:18:25.660 --> 00:18:29.579
is that you can have the same software

00:18:31.420 --> 00:18:35.859
in the same Docker instances, containers,

00:18:35.859 --> 00:18:39.540
and then if they're running on different hardware,

00:18:39.540 --> 00:18:43.020
you'll actually get different runtime values.

00:18:43.020 --> 00:18:46.020
So if we solve the matrix on the left

00:18:46.020 --> 00:18:49.540
with ARM or the middle with x86

00:18:49.540 --> 00:18:51.260
or on the right with RASC,

00:18:52.140 --> 00:18:54.579
you can see the number at the bottom is different.

00:18:54.579 --> 00:18:57.060
And as a R user, that's a little terrifying

00:18:57.060 --> 00:18:58.780
because I would think, oh,

00:18:58.780 --> 00:19:01.500
it's just maybe a small rounding error or something,

00:19:01.500 --> 00:19:05.819
but these small rounding errors are magnified

00:19:05.819 --> 00:19:07.219
in certain instances.

00:19:07.219 --> 00:19:10.699
And it's quite spooky, I think.

00:19:11.699 --> 00:19:14.140
When we do this in WebAssembly,

00:19:14.140 --> 00:19:16.780
because it's fully contained

00:19:16.780 --> 00:19:18.780
and it has the virtual operating system,

00:19:20.219 --> 00:19:23.300
this will produce a consistent answer every single time.

